        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer485056161" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17981256851706272397">A good novel that describes how the lives of the Arabs turned to be after the occupation of the Castalians to Andalucia (currently known as Spain). The book exhibits the different oppression the Arab went through, and how they were prohibited from practicing the Islamic rituals. They were forced to become Christians or die. And in many cases they were forced to leave their villages and places. The story navigates different periods of time through 6 generations; starts with telling a story of a g</span>
  <span id="freeText17981256851706272397" style="display:none">A good novel that describes how the lives of the Arabs turned to be after the occupation of the Castalians to Andalucia (currently known as Spain). The book exhibits the different oppression the Arab went through, and how they were prohibited from practicing the Islamic rituals. They were forced to become Christians or die. And in many cases they were forced to leave their villages and places. The story navigates different periods of time through 6 generations; starts with telling a story of a grandparents who witnessed the first years of Grenada's occupation up until the grand children of their grand children.<br />Arab people also suffered from excessive taxes, they were discriminated(even after they became Christians)because they were Arabs, and Slavery was very common (Arabs were the slaves of course).<br /><br />However, I didn't like the beginning of the story as I couldn't easily connect it to the rest of the book. The story starts by a vision that Abo Ga'afar (the first grandfather) saw about a dead beautiful woman on the bank of a river. The writer was not successful to easily tie this as an indication to the occupation of Granada. <br />Although the story mainly focuses on the details of the oppression the Arabs lived in Andalucia , I was anticipating to have a glimpse (a very small one) of how the Arab world was like. Who were the rulers and why they haven't interfered to save Andalucia. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17981256851706272397" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


