<div id="review_1910875228" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1910875228" />
    <a title="Maryam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38963028-maryam"><img alt="Maryam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1631049076p2/38963028.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1910875228?book_show_action=true">Feb 28, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maryam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maryam" href="/user/show/38963028-maryam">Maryam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1910875228&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1910875228" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5528490240794936256">There are many extraordinary things about this book.<br/>For starters, characters building was brilliant. Their descriptions, and their development. Generally speaking Radwa Ashour has this inexplicable talent of making the reader fall in love with the character without showing us much about him. The way she introduced Saad and Naeem and how they became friends made me all smiles. Not only that, but their relationship as a whole. Exhibit A: When Saad left and Naeem cursed his name and all the names h</span>
  <span id="freeText5528490240794936256" style="display:none">There are many extraordinary things about this book.<br />For starters, characters building was brilliant. Their descriptions, and their development. Generally speaking Radwa Ashour has this inexplicable talent of making the reader fall in love with the character without showing us much about him. The way she introduced Saad and Naeem and how they became friends made me all smiles. Not only that, but their relationship as a whole. Exhibit A: When Saad left and Naeem cursed his name and all the names he knew. There was also this scene where Abo Gaafar watched the books burn and then he died after stating his anger at God. In fact, all the monologues where characters were speaking to God were very powerful. The storyline of Saad and Salima was my favorite thing in the book, and the scenes of both of their deaths, are two of the most epic scenes I read in my life. It is brilliant and wholly powerful, how she died in half of a paragraph, and he, in a sentence. Don't get me started on Maryama as well. Maryama was the lovliest. A cunning, smart storyteller with all the humor and the endurance in world. She's the character in the book that witnessed most. Until the end of part 2, I was very much in love with the book. Then in part 3, life was calmer, following only Ali. It was a very depressing part, and I didn't want to read it because nothing was happening in it, but I kept reading it anyway. The last part was made up for by a heartbreaking grand closure. This was a sublime reading experience. 4.6/5.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5528490240794936256" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

